<dl id="n25185c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25185c">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25185c"> 185(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> valkirries <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25185c"><li>FW 68.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n25185c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n25185c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25185c">MS BL 47472-153v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:194 <a name="c3d" href="../../FF/fdra/cda.htm#c3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c3d.htm#n25185c">Draft: I.3&sect;1.3</a>/2.3/3.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">These heavenly maidens were not first imagined by himself <font color="green">[Muhammed]</font>. They are noticed in the Persian hymns, much earlier, as meeting the pious: they are the Apsaras (or &ldquo;watermovers&rdquo;) of the great Indian epic, who wed heroes in heaven; the <mark>Valkyries</mark> (&ldquo;hero-choosers&rdquo;), and swan maidens, of the Norse, which were the white clouds. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 239-40</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Valkyrie&mdash;In Scandinavian mythology, any of the twelve war-maidens who hovered over battlefields and conducted the fallen warriors (of their choice) to Valhalla. </mm> </dd></dl>
